window.docContents[137].resolve({"/Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory":{"contents":"This chapter covers additive combinatorics as it is formalised in mathlib: the basic\narithmetic of sumsets and the doubling constant, the Cauchy–Davenport bound on sumsets in\n, the Erdős–Ginzburg–Ziv theorem on zero-sum subsequences, the\nPlünnecke–Ruzsa inequalities together with the Ruzsa triangle and covering lemmas, Freiman\nhomomorphisms, and the structure theorems for sets of very small doubling. Throughout, ,\n,  denote finite subsets of a group  (written multiplicatively in the general\nstatements, additively where the result requires commutativity),  denotes cardinality,\nand  the product set (additively, the sumset\n). For a non-negative integer  we write  (additively ) for the -fold\nproduct set. The doubling constant of the pair  is , and a set has\nsmall doubling when  is not much larger than . Each mathlib-backed node\ncarries a (lean := …) reference naming the exact declaration, and its proof sketch follows the\nargument that declaration actually uses, naming the lemmas that proof invokes.\n\nThe final section records the Polynomial Freiman–Ruzsa (PFR) theorem — that a subset of\n with doubling  is covered by  cosets of a subgroup of size at\nmost  — supplied by the public teorth/pfr project. Those nodes are informal (the project\nbuilds against a different mathlib version); each records its declaration, an exact-source\npermalink, and that the formalisation is sorry-free. The PFR proof passes through an entropic\nformulation in which set-doubling is replaced by the Ruzsa distance between random variables, and\nit bridges back into the mathlib graph through the Ruzsa covering lemma and the additive\n bound that its endgame literally invokes.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean","header":"10. Additive and Combinatorial Number Theory","id":"/Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Additive-and-Combinatorial-Number-Theory"}});